<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Grafsha McDaughts</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Disciple<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Aug 2002<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Landragoran Heronwing</b><br /><i>If the items you get are completely buyable, if the characters are as well, then why work for anything?  No matter what you have, <b>you will impress no one, and the urge to impress others is what drives folks to play EQ.</b>  Take that away and the game will crash and burn even more swiftly.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Welcome to vapid generalizations. While there are likely folks who play to get items just to impress others ... personally, I doubt they are the majority. It is the "impress others" that I find hard to believe. That is even more shallow and silly than the progression of SOE selling items ingame. Ironically, SOE selling items ingame is more/less going to happen down the road ... if it is not going on already.<br />
<br />
What is lost in the game itself are the tiny little things that the majority of current players don't even know ever existed. That first set of banded armor; rangers questing for ivy; learning to tailor to get some decent cloth armor for your mage; bard lambert. Was the gear any good? Not by today's standards. Yet at the time it was decent, if not great, and it was something you ... worked and quested for. The path of the game was the value in the game.<br />
<br />
Things were done not to brag or show off or whatever ... but because that is how you got the best gear available. You could only get this gear by earning it or bartering with other players who were actually online at the time. You had to interact. You had to play. You had to progress in a stair step fashion from day one to ding 55 ... and those steps were tough (both ways!!!!).<br />
<br />
Today you can get from level 1 to 65 having never talked to a single player ingame ... never ... ever. You can start out in top of the line, raid drop gear at level 1. All you have to do is buy it. This is just staying in the game. The path is smoother if you spend more RL cash to 'acquire' game cash or characters or items. I ask, 'why would you?' It is a game. There is no holy grail at the end of it ... in point of fact, there is no end to it. No peak. <br />
<br />
You can claim an end. Conquer time and get an item for each slot in your inventory from there. Max a tradeskill; max all tradeskills. Get each character slot on a server filled with at lvl 65, elementally geared toon. Whatever ... but whatever you might call the end game. The point where you won the game, there is still so much that exists that you have not done or tried. There are still options. So many that no one can 'totally win the game.'<br />
<br />
For those who actually acquire gear to use as tokens of status are morons. In case you missed it - I said <b>MORONS</b>!!!! Of course, SOE recognizes that morons will pay for more and more pixel candy. Morons are too stupid to realize that even if an item only costs 1 penny, that 1 penny is in reality worth more than any pixel candy you can purchace.<br />
<br />
Given business management, the real underlying question in this poll gives SOE one single answer: if the player base wants secure transactions, then SOE can buy up Yantis and keep it tranparently separate from the game, provide a secure transaction path and monopolize the selling of items so all the money goes into their coffers. SOE can play both ends of the transaction game while focusing on keeping any competitors out of their market ... without any player ever knowing they are simply paying SOE for items.<br />
<br />
If you voted yes, or in any way can justify selling any ingame item for real life cash, or have paid cash for pixel candy ... welcome to being the moron. If your enjoyment in this game is based on acquiring items by any available method because having those items makes you feel cool and gives you bragging rights ... you have crossed the line and are a stupid f***ing moron.<br />
<br />
That there is any shaman who can justify the Yantis practice and now the SOE entry into that market shows how far downhill this game has gone.</p>
	
	
	
