<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Ancere</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Initiate<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Oct 2002<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Allowing items to be sold in-game for cash would create a very interesting and competitive environment. I hate the concept of buying/selling characters through Yantis or the like, it goes against the spirit of the game IMO.<br />
<br />
However, If I had a sellable item that I no longer used (and would normally sell it to a vendor for chump change) the allure of getting real cash for that item would be very tempting. Hell, sell enough things and you could make playing EQ profitable, or at least cost nothing.<br />
<br />
But, the concepts of CAWU and any other altruistic method of loot distribution would go right out the window. If a valuable (sellable) item dropped for a group it would no longer matter who could best use it, or if it was an upgrade. Or better yet, what if your guild was raiding VT and a rare (hence expensive) tradeskill component dropped, the guild leaders would be placed in an awkward position of having loot with real cash value under their fingertips. I can imagine guilds forming for the sole purpose of raiding for loot to sell and distribute real cash to its members.<br />
<br />
This would change the entire culture of EQ.<br />
<br />
Ancere</p>
	
	
	
	
	
